'''1960年代反文化运动'''（{{lang-en| 1960s counterculture movement}}）是一种[[反文化|反文化]][[反建制|反体制]]行为，这种现象首先发生在[[英国|英国]]和[[美国|美国]]，之后在[[1960年代|1960年代]]初至[[70年代|70年代]]中期在[[西方世界|西方世界]]大规模传播。[[伦敦|伦敦]]、[[纽约|纽约]]和[[旧金山|旧金山]]是早期反文化活动的温床。随着[[非裔美国人民权运动|美国民权运动]]的演进，反文化运动获得了进一步发展，并随着[[美国政府|美国政府]]对越南[[越战|军事干预]]的扩大而演变为一场革命性的运动。<ref>[[Eric_Donald_Hirsch|Hirsch, E. D.]] (1993). ''The Dictionary of Cultural Literacy''. Houghton Mifflin. ISBN 978-0-395-65597-9. p. 419. "Members of a cultural protest that began in the U.S. in the 1960s and affected Europe before fading in the 1970s ... fundamentally a cultural rather than a political protest."</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Anderson| first = Terry H.| title = The Movement and the Sixties| url = https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195074093| publisher = Oxford University Press| year = 1995| isbn = 978-0-19-510457-8 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Landis|editor1-first=Judson R.|title=Current Perspectives on Social Problems|url=https://archive.org/details/currentperspecti0000land|date=1973|publisher=Wadsworth Publishing Co.|location=Belmont, California|isbn=0-534-00289-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/currentperspecti0000land/page/2 2]|edition=Third|quote=Culture is the "social heritage" of society. It includes the complex set of learned and shared beliefs, customs, skills, habits, traditions, and knowledge common to the members of society. Within a culture, there may be subcultures made up of specific groups that are somewhat separate from the rest of society because of distinct traits, beliefs, or interests.}}</ref>自1960年代以降，美国在一些社会议题上也出现了广泛的紧张态势，其中例如体现在[[人类性行为|人类性行为]]、[[妇女权利|妇女权利]]、[[精神药物|精神药物]]实验、对传统权威的态度以及对[[美国梦|美国梦]]的诠释。与这些争议问题有关的运动在1960年代的反文化潮流中诞生以及发展。

随着这场运动的发展，许多新的文化形式、[[亚文化|亚文化]]先后诞生，[[波希米亚主义|波希米亚主义]]、[[嬉皮士|嬉皮士]]等另类文化及生活方式应运而生。这种现象在[[英国入侵|英国入侵]]时期尤其明显，[[披头士乐队|披头士乐队]]和其他一些电影制作人的作品受到[[审查制度|审查制度]]的限制。除了创造流行趋势的披头士乐队，其他许多的创意艺术家、作家和思想家，在许多行业和专业内部，推波助澜地定义反文化。

有几个因素将1960年代反文化运动与以前的反独裁运动区分开来。[[第二次世界大战|第二次世界大战]]战后的“[[婴儿潮|婴儿潮]]”<ref name="CNN 2011-08-11">{{cite news |url=http://i2.cdn.turner.com/money/2011/08/11/pf/recession_birth_rate/chart-birth-rate-2.top.gif |format=GIF |title=Birth Rate Chart |work=CNN |publisher=CNN |date=August 11, 2011 |quote=Annotated Chart of 20th Century US Birth Rates |accessdate=2017-02-23 |archive-date=2021-01-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210107163114/https://i2.cdn.turner.com/money/2011/08/11/pf/recession_birth_rate/chart-birth-rate-2.top.gif |dead-url=no }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boomerslife.org/baby_boom_population_us_census_bureau_by_state.htm |title=Baby Boom population - U.S. Census Bureau - USA and by state |publisher=Boomerslife.org |accessdate=June 9, 2009 |archive-date=2009-06-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605062254/http://www.boomerslife.org/baby_boom_population_us_census_bureau_by_state.htm |dead-url=no }}</ref>产生了前所未有的数量的潜在的对社会不满的年轻人，他们作为美国社会的潜在参与者，重新思考了美国民主主义发展的方向。战后美国国内充裕的财富也使得他们不必过于关注自身及家庭的财政状况，而这些物质必需品是他们主要生活在[[大萧条|大萧条]]时期的父母所必须关心的。<ref name="Yale-New Haven Teachers Institute">{{cite journal |title=Student Protest in the 1960s |journal=Yale-New Haven Teachers Institute: Curriculum Unit 79.02.03 |year=1979 |last=Churney |first=Linda |url=http://www.yale.edu/ynhti/curriculum/units/1979/2/79.02.03.x.html |accessdate=April 18, 2014 |quote=This unit focuses on student protest in the 60s |author= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729084756/http://www.yale.edu/ynhti/curriculum/units/1979/2/79.02.03.x.html |archive-date=2016-07-29 |dead-url=yes }}</ref>这个时代值得注意的是，这场运动中的一系列行为和其起因的很大一部分很快被主流社会所吸收，特别是在美国。<ref name="KidnerBucur2007">{{cite book|author1=Frank Kidner|author2=Maria Bucur|author3=Ralph Mathisen|author4=Sally McKee|author5=Theodore Weeks|title=Making Europe: People, Politics, and Culture, Volume II: Since 1550|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yIMSNu5OFHoC&pg=PA831|date=December 27, 2007|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=0-618-00481-5|pages=831–|access-date=2017-02-23|archive-date=2020-07-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200729184219/https://books.google.com/books?id=yIMSNu5OFHoC&pg=PA831|dead-url=no}}</ref><ref name="RubinCasper2013">{{cite book|author1=Professor Joan Shelley Rubin|author2=Professor Scott E. Casper|title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of American Cultural and Intellectual History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_-lMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA264|date=March 14, 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-976435-8|pages=264–|access-date=2017-02-23|archive-date=2020-07-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200729200622/https://books.google.com/books?id=_-lMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA264|dead-url=no}}</ref><ref name="Kimball2013">{{cite book|author=Roger Kimball|title=The Long March: How the Cultural Revolution of the 1960s Changed America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DqXNlJxslm4C&pg=PT82|date=October 10, 2013|publisher=Encounter Books|isbn=978-1-59403-393-3|pages=82–|access-date=2017-02-23|archive-date=2020-07-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200729184204/https://books.google.com/books?id=DqXNlJxslm4C&pg=PT82|dead-url=no}}</ref>

反文化运动基本始于1963年11月[[肯尼迪遇刺案|肯尼迪总统被刺杀事件]]，它伴随着美国军事介入[[东南亚|东南亚]]的终止和1973年征兵法案的终止而融入流行文化，最终结束于1974年8月[[尼克松|尼克松]]辞去[[美国总统|美国总统]]一职。

广义上看，1960年代的反文化运动从多方面来讲作为一个社会催化剂，使那个时代产生了突飞猛进的变化。

